ocuses on 21C permutations of folk monstrosity, the collection is transhistorical in approach, featuring chapters that focus on contemporary folk monsters, historical antecedents, and the pre-C21st art and media traditions that shaped enduring monstrous beings. The collection also illuminates how folk monsters and folk “horror” travel across cultures, media, and time periods, and how iconic monsters are tethered to yet repeatedly become unanchored from material and regional contexts.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aMonsters in mass media. 0aMonsters in popular culture. 0aMonstersvFolklore. 4aCultural Studies. 4aFilm, Media, and Communication. 4aInterdisciplinary Studies. 4aMedia Studies. 4aPsychology. 7aPERFORMING ARTS / Film / Genres / Horror.2bisacsh  aMonsters, folk, immateriality, regionality, folkloresque, Gothic.1 aBacchilega, Cristina, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBalanzategui, Jessica, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBalanzategui, Jessica, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aCraven, Allison, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCraven, Allison, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aGaunson, Stephen, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGreenhill, Pauline, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHock Soon Ng, Andrew, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHorsley, Karen, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLater, Naja, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLynch, Andrew, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMaguire, Emma, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov